ummary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test implementation issues**\\n\\nI need to remember not to use \\\"$\\\" in class names since our test has underscores instead. I’ll check the build results to see if the generated class exists; if it doesn’t, I might need to run a compile. There's a guideline against compiling or running tests, so I’ll stick to creating a Java test source under the correct package. I’m also exploring MethodHandles for private access, but I'll avoid reflection directly unless necessary. There's potential coverage issues; it could be a problem with how the library classes are instrumented.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring potential compilation issues**\\n\\nIt seems like the class might not have been generated due to a compilation failure. I suspect we need to refine our approach since past attempts didn’t succeed. Upon inspecting the build.gradle diffs, it’s odd there are no imports, and many untracked files suggest our repository might have untracked generated tests. I should check if the generated access classes' output doesn’t appear in the native image. Additionally, the test method might be catching errors too broadly, which could affect coverage.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing class initialization issues**\\n\\nI’m considering that since the class$ method is static, invoking it might trigger class initialization, which could lead to failures in the Groovy runtime on native. Existing tests catch some of these issues. For coverage in the native agent, if class initialization fails, the call site won’t be reached. I want to avoid initializing the original closure class. I’m wondering if Java’s invokestatic triggers this, especially since existing tests sometimes create child-loaded classes that bypass Groovy’s static initialization.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_6RuFT93ew7DKVWK998eivORO|fc_048ce75e57497644016a012cbf93348192888156884c472402", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "tmp=$